<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Characteristic Species</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Achnatherum</i> <i>hymenoides</i> is dominant or co-dominant in the herbaceous layer with <i>Bromus</i> <i>rubens</i>, <i>Bromus</i> <i>tectorum</i>, <i>Elymus</i> <i>elymoides</i>, <i>Erodium</i> <i>cicutarium</i>, <i>Hesperostipa</i> <i>comata</i>, <i>Koeleria</i> <i>macrantha</i>, <i>Lessingia</i> spp., <i>Nassella</i> <i>cernua</i>, <i>Pascopyrum</i> <i>smithii</i> and <i>Poa</i> <i>secunda</i>. Emergent shrubs may be present at low cover, including <i>Atriplex</i> <i>confertifolia</i> or <i>Atriplex</i> <i>spinifera</i>. </div>
</div>

        
	
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Vegetation Layers</h4>
	<div class="text">  Herbs < 1.5 m; cover is open to intermittent. </div>
</div>

        
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Membership Rules</h4>
	<ul class="text">
		
		<li><i>Achnatherum hymenoides</i> > 50% relative cover in the herbaceous layer, but usually in sparsely vegetated sandy areas (Thomas et al. 2004).</li>
		
	</ul>
</div>

        
	
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Habitats</h4>
	<div class="text"> All topographic locations. Soils are sandy with many derived from aeolian deposits.  </div>
</div>

        
