<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Remarks</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Achnatherum hymenoides </i>is a native perennial bunchgrass that tolerates low nutrient and water levels. Germination of seeds is low unless scarified, aged, or stratified (Griffith and Booth 1988, Jones and Neilson 1992). Seedling establishment is high under moist conditions. Culms green up in the fall and begin growing when spring temperatures become favorable. Plants continue growing into early summer, with more carbohydrates becoming stored in the crowns than in the roots by the end of the growing season (Tirmenstein 1999a). The botanical literature often refers to this species as <i>Oryzopsis hymenoides </i>or <i>Stipa hymenoides. <br/>
<br/>
</i>The alliance occurs throughout the Great Basin and adjacent western Great Plains (NatureServe 2007a). <i>A. hymenoides </i>is a component of many transmontane California alliances, but stands are rare in California. All stands known in California occur on sandy substrates, including sand dunes. In some cases, <i>A. hymenoides </i>may locally dominate on degraded areas of <i>Atriplex confertifolia </i>shrublands, such as those seen along the Death Valley Highway at the junction with Darwin Road. </div>
</div>

    
	
	
